# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iupac
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:iupac/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:iupac/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The **International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry** (**IUPAC** /ˈaɪjuːpæk, ˈjuː-/) is an international federation of National Adhering Organizations working for the advancement of the chemical sciences, especially by developing nomenclature and terminology.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] It is a member of the International Science Council (ISC).
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC is registered in Zürich, Switzerland, and its administrative office, known as the "IUPAC Secretariat", is in Research Triangle Park, North Carolina, United States.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC was established in 1919 as the successor of the International Congress of Applied Chemistry for the advancement of chemistry.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Its members, the National Adhering Organizations, can be national chemistry societies, national academies of sciences, or just other bodies representing chemists.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] There are a total of fifty-four National Adhering Organizations and three Associate National Adhering Organizations.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC's Inter-divisional Committee on Nomenclature and Symbols (IUPAC nomenclature) is the recognized world authority in developing standards for naming chemical elements and compounds.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Since its creation, IUPAC has been run by many different committees with different responsibilities.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] These committees run different projects; of those which include standardizing nomenclature, finding ways to bring chemistry to the world, and publishing works.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC is best known for its works standardizing nomenclature in chemistry, but they have publications in many science fields including chemistry, biology, and physics.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Some important work IUPAC has done in these fields includes standardizing nucleotide base sequence code names; publishing books for environmental scientists, chemists, and physicists; and improving education in science.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC is also known for standardizing the atomic weights of the elements through one of its oldest standing committees, the Commission on Isotopic Abundances and Atomic Weights (CIAAW).
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The need for an international standard for chemistry was first addressed in 1860 by a committee headed by German scientist Friedrich August Kekulé von Stradonitz.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] This committee was the first international conference to create an international naming system for organic compounds.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The ideas that were formulated at that conference evolved into the official IUPAC nomenclature of organic chemistry.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC is a legacy of this meeting, making it one of the most important historical international collaborations of chemistry societies.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC as such was established in 1919.Since this time, IUPAC has been the official organization with the responsibility of updating and maintaining official organic nomenclature.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] One notable country excluded from early IUPAC was Germany.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Germany's exclusion was a result of prejudice towards it by the Allied powers after World War I.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Germany was finally admitted into IUPAC in 1929.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] However, Nazi Germany was removed from IUPAC during World War II.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] At this time, IUPAC was affiliated with the Allied powers, but had little involvement with the war effort itself.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] East and West Germany were only readmitted to IUPAC in 1973.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Since World War II, IUPAC has focused on standardizing nomenclature and methods in science.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] In 2016, IUPAC denounced the use of chlorine as a chemical weapon.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] In a letter to Ahmet Üzümcü, director of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW), the organization pointed out their concerns in regards to chlorine weapon usage in the Syrian civil war and other places .
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The letter stated, "Our organizations deplore the use of chlorine in this manner.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC is governed by several committees that all have different responsibilities.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Each committee is made up of members of different National Adhering Organizations from different countries.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Scientists framed a systematic method for naming organic compounds based on their structures.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Hence, the naming rules were formulated by IUPAC.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC establishes rules for harmonized spelling of some chemicals to reduce variation among different local English-language variants.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] For example, they recommend "aluminium" rather than "aluminum", "sulfur" rather than "sulphur", and "caesium" rather than "cesium".
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC organic nomenclature has three main parts: the substituents, carbon chain length, and chemical affix.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The substituents are any functional groups tied to the main carbon chain.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The main carbon chain is the longest possible continuous chain.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The chemical affix denotes what type of molecule it is.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] For example, the ending *ane* conveys a single bonded carbon chain, as in "hexane" (C 6H 14).
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] Basic IUPAC inorganic nomenclature has two main parts: the cation and the anion.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The *cation* is the name for the positively charged ion and the *anion* is the name for the negatively charged ion.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC also has a system for giving codes to identify amino acids and nucleotide bases.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] It needed a coding system that represented long sequences of amino acids.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] This would allow for these sequences to be compared to try to find homologies.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] These codes can consist of either a one-letter code, or a three-letter code.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] These codes make it easier and shorter to write down the amino acid sequences that make up proteins.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The nucleotide bases are made up of purines (adenine and guanine) and pyrimidines (cytosine and thymine or uracil).
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] These nucleotide bases make up DNA and RNA.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] And they make the genome of an organism much smaller and easier to read.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The *Experimental Thermodynamics* books series covers many topics in the fields of thermodynamics.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC colour code their books in order to make each publication distinguishable.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC and UNESCO were the lead organizations coordinating events for the International Year of Chemistry, which took place in 2011.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The International Year of Chemistry was originally proposed by IUPAC at the general assembly in Turin, Italy.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] This motion was adopted by UNESCO at a meeting in 2008.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] The main objectives of the International Year of Chemistry were to increase public appreciation of chemistry and gain more interest in the world of chemistry.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] This event is also being held to encourage young people to get involved and contribute to chemistry.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] A further reason for this event being held is to honour how chemistry has made improvements to everyone's way of life.
[src:iupac/international-union-of-pure-and-applied-chemistry] IUPAC Presidents are elected by the IUPAC Council during the General Assembly.
